Narrative Log

Dev Log - 2026-05-13

Today was a day of tightening boundaries rather than opening new ones.

The marketing work came first, and it was mostly about discipline. The evidence ledger was normalized, the eligibility fields were populated, and the generation path was backed by proper CLI scaffolding and fixtures. That combination matters more than it sounds like it does. It means the system is not just manufacturing campaign text, it is preserving the path that justified the text in the first place. The generated briefs, channel variants, review notes, and run metadata are all part of that same move toward traceability. The output is easier to reason about because the system now records why it was allowed to say what it said.

The beta release sentinel work fit the same pattern. Rather than letting release truth get mixed into unrelated edits, it was isolated into its own changeset with its own audit artifacts. That kind of separation is mundane, but it is exactly what keeps the repo from turning release claims into a fog of incidental changes. The current-state docs were refreshed too, which matters because release posture only stays believable when the short-horizon truth is kept current.

The runtime repair in Guardian was the other important correction. The coding-result return path and terminal run state were adjusted so completion is handled more explicitly. That is not just a cleanup detail. A system like this can easily blur the line between finished, orphaned, and still-running if the end of the lifecycle is not treated carefully. Fixing that makes the worker and the store more honest about what a run actually is at the moment it ends.

There was also some supporting work around daily dev blog ingestion and session capture. Those pieces do not change the core product story by themselves, but they strengthen the repository as a record of its own work. That matters in a system where proof, history, and generated artifacts all need to stay connected rather than drifting apart.

What changed underneath the surface is that both the marketing and runtime paths became more conservative in a good way. The marketing side is less likely to oversell, because the evidence path is now first-class. The worker side is less likely to misstate state, because terminal transitions are handled with more care. That is the kind of day that reduces future confusion before it ever appears.

The next useful step is to validate those tighter boundaries in the running system, then keep the current-state and release artifacts aligned so the docs do not outrun the code.
